18 (8)(a) For the purposes of subsection (2) of this section, an individual is considered to have
19 committed a disqualifying act when the individual:
20 (A) Fails to comply with the terms and conditions of a reasonable written policy established by
21 the employer or through collective bargaining, which may include blanket, random, periodic and
22 probable cause testing, that governs the use, sale, possession or effects of drugs, cannabis or alcohol
23 in the workplace;
24 (B) Fails or refuses to take a drug, cannabis or alcohol test as required by the employer’s rea-
25 sonable written policy;
26 (C) Refuses to cooperate with or subverts or attempts to subvert a drug, cannabis or alcohol
27 testing process in any employment-related test required by the employer’s reasonable written policy,
28 including but not limited to:
29 (i) Refusal or failure to complete proper documentation that authorizes the test;
30 (ii) Refusal or failure to sign a chain of custody form;
31 (iii) Presentation of false identification;
32 (iv) Placement of an adulterant in the individual’s specimen for testing, when the adulterant is
33 identified by a testing facility; or
34 (v) Interference with the accuracy of the test results by conduct that includes dilution or
35 adulteration of a test specimen;
36 (D) Is under the influence of intoxicants while performing services for the employer;
37 (E) Possesses cannabis or a drug unlawfully or in violation of the employer’s reasonable written
38 policy during work;
39 (F) Tests positive for alcohol, cannabis or an unlawful drug in connection with employment; or
40 (G) Refuses to enter into or violates the terms of a last chance agreement with the employer.
41 (b)(A) Except as provided in subparagraph (B) of this paragraph, an individual is not considered
42 to have committed a disqualifying act under this subsection if the individual, on the date of sepa-
43 ration or within 10 days after the date of separation, is participating in a recognized drug, cannabis
44 or alcohol rehabilitation program and provides documentation of participation in the program to the
45 department.
