8 present in an individual’s body exceeds the amount prescribed in a collective bargaining agreement
9 or the amount prescribed in the employer’s reasonable written policy if there is no applicable col-
10 lective bargaining agreement provision.
11 SECTION 8. ORS 657.202 is amended to read:
12 657.202. (1) As used in this section, “temporary lockout benefits” means benefits payable as
13 provided in this section to individuals who are unemployed due to a lockout, as defined in ORS
14 662.205.
15 (2) An individual is eligible to receive temporary lockout benefits for a week in an amount equal
16 to the weekly benefit amount of the individual’s most recent unemployment benefit claim if:
17 (a) Prior to the week, the individual has received all of the regular benefits that were available
18 to the individual under this chapter;
19 (b) The individual is not eligible for any other benefits, including benefits provided under any
20 federal law extending benefits beyond those provided for as regular benefits; and
21 (c) At the time of filing an initial or additional claim, the individual is unemployed due to a
22 lockout at the individual’s place of employment.
23 (3) The maximum temporary lockout benefit amount an individual may receive under this section
24 is 26 times the weekly benefit amount of the individual’s most recent unemployment benefit claim.
25 (4) Notwithstanding subsections (2) and (3) of this section, temporary lockout benefits otherwise
26 payable to an individual under this section may not be paid for weeks that begin after the week in
27 which the lockout ends.
28 (5) An employer shall be charged for temporary lockout benefits in the manner provided in this
29 chapter for charging employers for regular benefits.
30 SECTION 9. ORS 657.400 is amended to read:
31 657.400. (1) There is established in the State Treasury, separate and distinct from the General
32 Fund, the Employment Department Special Fraud Control Fund. The Employment Department Spe-
33 cial Fraud Control Fund shall consist of moneys collected or received by the Employment Depart-
34 ment as follows:
35 (a) Interest and penalties described under ORS 657.310 [(8)(b)] (7)(b).
36 (b) All gifts to, interest on or profits earned by the Employment Department Special Fraud
37 Control Fund.
38 (2) The moneys in the Employment Department Special Fraud Control Fund are continuously
39 appropriated to the Employment Department and may not be appropriated, transferred or otherwise
40 made available to any other state agency.
41 (3) All amounts in the Employment Department Special Fraud Control Fund shall be used for
42 the following purposes, as included in the biennial budget of the Employment Department and ap-
43 proved by the Legislative Assembly:
44 (a) Administrative costs associated with the prevention, discovery and collection of unemploy-
45 ment benefit overpayments;
[10]

HB 4109
1 (b) Costs associated with the Lost Wages Assistance program administered by the department
2 pursuant to a grant agreement with the Federal Emergency Management Agency under authority
3 established by the presidential memorandum issued on August 8, 2020, on the subject of Authorizing
4 the Other Needs Assistance Program for Major Disaster Declarations Related to Coronavirus Dis-
5 ease 2019; and
6 (c) Administrative costs associated with other benefit programs administered by the department.
7 (4) If, under subsection (3)(b) of this section, the Employment Department uses any amounts for
8 the purpose of reimbursing the Federal Emergency Management Agency for overpayments of bene-
9 fits under the Lost Wages Assistance program:
10 (a) Any amounts of overpayments collected from the debtor by the department shall be deposited
11 in the Employment Department Special Fraud Control Fund.
12 (b)(A) The department may collect such overpayments under the provisions of this chapter as
13 if the amounts were overpayments of regular benefits; or
14 (B) The Director of the Employment Department may waive collection of such overpayments if
15 the director determines that it is administratively impracticable to pursue collection.
